# C++ Programming Techniques (Core + Practical)

## 1. Modular Programming

Break code into small reusable units.

* Use functions, classes, headers
* Separate `.h` and `.cpp`

👉 Example:

// math_utils.h
int add(int a, int b);

// math_utils.cpp
int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }


✔️ Used in: All real-world systems

---

## 2. Abstraction

Hide implementation, show only interface.

class Engine {
public:
    void start(); // user sees this
};

✔️ Used in: APIs, libraries

---

## 3. Encapsulation

Protect data using access control.

class BankAccount {
private:
    double balance;

public:
    void deposit(double amt) { balance += amt; }
};

✔️ Prevents misuse of data

---

## 4. RAII (Very Important)

**Resource Acquisition Is Initialization**

👉 Tie resource lifetime to object lifetime

class File {
public:
    File() { /* open file */ }
    ~File() { /* close file */ }
};

✔️ Used in:

* File handling
* Memory management
* Smart pointers

---

## 5. Smart Pointers (Modern Technique)

Avoid manual `new/delete`

* `std::unique_ptr`
* `std::shared_ptr`

auto ptr = std::make_unique<int>(10);

✔️ Prevents memory leaks

---

## 6. Const Correctness

Write safer code

void print(const std::string& name);

✔️ Guarantees no modification

---

## 7. Pass by Reference vs Value

Avoid unnecessary copying

void update(std::vector<int>& v); // efficient

✔️ Performance optimization

---

## 8. Template Programming

Write generic reusable code

template<typename T>
T add(T a, T b) {
    return a + b;
}

✔️ Used in STL, libraries

---

## 9. STL Usage (Key Technique)

Use standard library instead of reinventing

std::vector<int> v = {1,2,3};
std::sort(v.begin(), v.end());

✔️ Cleaner and faster development

---

## 10. Algorithmic Thinking

Efficient problem solving

* Use correct data structures
* Optimize time/space

✔️ Used in:

* Trading systems
* Game engines
* Simulations

---

## 11. Function Objects (Functors)

More powerful than function pointers(normal function)

struct Multiply {
    int operator()(int x) { return x * x; }
};

✔️ Used in STL algorithms

---

## 12. Lambda Expressions (Modern C++)

Inline functions

std::sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b) {
    return a > b;
});

✔️ Cleaner than functors

---

## 13. Design Patterns

Reusable architecture solutions

* Singleton
* Factory
* Strategy
* Observer
* Command

---

## 14. Error Handling

Use exceptions properly

try {
    throw std::runtime_error("Error");
} catch (...) {
}

✔️ Used in robust systems

---

## 15. Separation of Concerns

Divide system into layers

Example:

* UI (menu)
* Logic
* Data

✔️ Very important for your console projects

---

## 16. Compile-Time Programming

Use `constexpr`, templates

constexpr int square(int x) {
    return x * x;
}

✔️ High-performance systems

---

## 17. Code Reusability

Avoid duplication

* Use utility classes
* Use templates
* Use inheritance carefully

---

## 18. Clean Code Practices

* Meaningful variable names
* Small functions
* Avoid deep nesting

